{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2009"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2009"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.05,0.11,0.37,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34217"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"9641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13720"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents with sudden onset, severe, chest pain radiating to his back. The patient describes experiencing episodes of joint pain and fatigue in the past, but he has not experienced any recent exacerbations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon physical examination, the patient appears anxious, diaphoretic, and is noted to be very tall. His blood pressure is 165/75mmHg in his right arm, and 138/70 mmHg in his left. Cardiac auscultation reveals an early diastolic murmur, best heard on the left lower sternal border, at the 3\u003Csup\u003Erd\u003C/sup\u003E and 4\u003Csup\u003Eth\u003C/sup\u003E intercostal spaces. An urgent CT scan is performed, revealing an intimal flap just proximal to the aortic root, and a dilated aorta with a double-lumen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"The presence of which one of the following physical signs would be most suggestive of the likely underlying condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ectopia lentis","Pectus carinatum","Steinberg thumb sign","High-arched palate","Mitral valve prolapse"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s chest pain is the result of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic root dissection\u003C/strong\u003E. Given his age, it is likely that an inherited disease is a pre-disposing risk factor. In context of his tall height, and previous episodes of joint pain and fatigue, \u003Cstrong\u003EMarfan\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMarfan\u0027s syndrome is a systemic disorder of \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E, that is inherited in an \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal dominant\u003C/strong\u003E pattern. It affects males and females equally, and is thought to affect ~1 per 5,000 people.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMarfan\u0027s syndrome commonly affects the skeletal, ocular and cardiovascular systems. \u0022Typical\u0022 features include tall and thin build with disproportionately long limbs, a high-arched palate, hyper extensible joints, pectus excavatum, scoliosis and intraocular lens dislocation. Patients with Marfan\u0027s syndrome are at increased risk of pneumothorax and vascular complications (i.e. aortic dissection, dilation and aneurysm). While genetic testing can be performed to assist diagnosis, diagnosis is commonly made on the basis of clinical features using the \u003Cstrong\u003EGhent criteria\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopia lentis \u003C/strong\u003E(the dislocation of the lens)\u003Cstrong\u003E is the most specific \u003C/strong\u003Eand characteristic ocular feature, aligning with the major diagnostic criteria outlined in the Ghent criteria. While other features such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epectus carinatum, Steinberg thumb sign (distal phalanx seen to protrude beyond ulnar border of clenched fists), high-arched palate, and mitral valve prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E are also associated with Marfan\u0027s syndrome, they are less specific. The revised Ghent criteria (\u003Cem\u003Esee image below\u003C/em\u003E) notes aortic root dissection and ectopia lentis as cardinal clinical features, and the presence of these two manifestations is sufficient for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of ectopia lentis, or a dislocated lens, is the most specific feature for diagnosing Marfan\u2019s syndrome in a patient with an aortic root dissection."],"references":["Judge DP, Dietz HC. Marfan\u0027s syndrome. Lancet. 2005 Dec 3;366(9501):1965-76.","Loeys BL, Dietz HC, Braverman AC, et al The revised Ghent nosology for the Marfan syndrome Journal of Medical Genetics 2010;47:476-485."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34217"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2009"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20898"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20898"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mz5zLkPAXWqxgQIrXpzsGLGyrYOf0f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mz5zLkPAXWqxgQIrXpzsGLGyrYOf0f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":812,"height":1146}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34217"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-24T10:15:51+09:30